WEBVTT

00:00.467 --> 00:04.269
<i>OLDER TED: In March of 2009,</i>
<i>I'd been dating my</i>
<i>high school girlfriend Karen</i>

00:04.271 --> 00:05.104
<i>for a few weeks.</i>

00:05.106 --> 00:07.039
<i>My friends</i>
<i>could not have</i>
<i>been less excited.</i>

00:07.041 --> 00:08.440
Hey, everybody.

00:08.442 --> 00:09.341
ALL: Hello.

00:09.343 --> 00:11.310
Sorry, we can't stay long.

00:11.312 --> 00:12.177
(ALL EXCLAIM)

00:12.179 --> 00:13.412
What a shame!
That is sad!

00:13.414 --> 00:15.347
Hey,
are those real
diamond earrings?

00:15.349 --> 00:18.317
Yes. Yes, they are. Thank you.

00:18.319 --> 00:20.252
I didn't say
I liked them.

00:20.254 --> 00:22.454
Oh, well, I got
a great deal on
them, so...

00:22.456 --> 00:25.457
Cool. I'm sure all
the exploited diamond
miners in Sierra Leone

00:25.459 --> 00:29.428
would give you a high-five
if they still had all
their fingers,

00:29.430 --> 00:31.463
but really pretty.

00:31.465 --> 00:32.564
Meet me upstairs.

00:32.566 --> 00:35.701
They only need one finger
to give her what I'm thinking.

00:35.703 --> 00:38.704
Yeah.
Ted, Karen's a douche.

00:38.706 --> 00:40.639
Wow. Thanks for
sugarcoating it.

00:40.641 --> 00:42.341
"Douche" is
sugarcoating it.

00:42.343 --> 00:46.612
Okay, believe it or not,
my friends do not get
a vote on who I date.

00:46.614 --> 00:48.647
It's my life.
I call the shots.

00:48.649 --> 00:51.483
Ted, now!
Yeah, coming!

00:51.485 --> 00:55.687
I don't know
what Ted sees in
that horrible woman.

00:55.689 --> 00:58.624
I mean, yeah,
she's got boobs, but...

00:58.626 --> 00:59.691
I guess I get it.

00:59.693 --> 01:01.727
I think it's 'cause
they met in high school.

01:01.729 --> 01:03.829
She was his
first real girlfriend.

01:03.831 --> 01:05.464
We look at Karen
and see a jerk.

01:05.466 --> 01:08.400
Ted looks at Karen and sees
the first person to touch
his wiener

01:08.402 --> 01:10.836
besides himself,
his mom and his
pediatrician.

01:10.838 --> 01:13.639
Okay, well,
it's almost 2:00 a.m.
I better get ready for work.

01:13.641 --> 01:16.775
How can
they call that thing
you're on a morning show?

01:16.777 --> 01:21.380
4:00 a.m. is still
the middle of the night.
I don't see how you do it.

01:21.382 --> 01:24.116
It's been almost a month.
I'm used to it.

01:24.118 --> 01:25.851
Plus the show's
not half bad,
right?

01:25.853 --> 01:28.520
Totally.
We've never seen it.

01:29.322 --> 01:30.489
Have you guys
ever watched it?

01:30.491 --> 01:32.324
Of course!
They've never seen it.

01:32.326 --> 01:34.259
Really?
What is your
favorite segment?

01:34.261 --> 01:35.327
Weather.
Never seen it.

01:35.329 --> 01:36.728
You guys have
never seen my
show?

01:36.730 --> 01:37.796
Sorry.
It's true.

01:37.798 --> 01:38.997
That's what I've been saying.

01:38.999 --> 01:42.601
Okay, yes, it's dull
and generic and we get
spanked in the ratings

01:42.603 --> 01:46.538
by that Korean channel that
only shows Kim Jong Il
riding a horse,

01:46.540 --> 01:50.242
but, guys,
it would mean so
much to me if just once

01:50.244 --> 01:53.812
I knew
my friends were
out there watching.

01:54.581 --> 01:55.614
I'll tell you what,

01:55.616 --> 01:58.550
this Friday morning, everyone
can come to our place,
3:30 a.m.

01:58.552 --> 02:02.621
We'll all put on PJ's.
We'll watch Robin's show.

02:02.623 --> 02:04.323
Aw, you guys are the best.

02:04.325 --> 02:05.791
We just want to support you.

02:05.793 --> 02:08.894
(WHINING) I just
want to go to sleep.

02:08.896 --> 02:12.764
I hate Robin for not
being more successful.

02:12.766 --> 02:14.399
Hey, guys.

02:14.401 --> 02:15.400
(ALL GROANING)

02:15.402 --> 02:20.239
Sad announcement.
Karen broke up with me.

02:21.708 --> 02:22.608
Go ahead.

02:22.610 --> 02:24.643
I knew you were
listening! Yes!

02:24.645 --> 02:26.411
(WHOOPING)

02:39.526 --> 02:40.325
(CHEERING)

02:40.327 --> 02:43.428
Hey, hey,
we shouldn't
be celebrating.

02:43.430 --> 02:45.864
Ted's just been
through a bad breakup.

02:45.866 --> 02:49.334
Look, buddy,
tell us everything.
Tell us what happened.

02:49.336 --> 02:50.669
Seriously,
spare no details.

02:50.671 --> 02:55.007
What did she say?
What did you say?
How did it feel?

02:55.009 --> 03:00.445
If you were to do it again,
all over, would you maybe...

03:01.848 --> 03:02.848
How did it happen?

03:02.850 --> 03:04.016
(SCOFFS) It was
the stupidest thing.

03:04.018 --> 03:08.921
I mean, we
were just hanging out,
you know, being funny.

03:08.923 --> 03:11.490
You're the fan
of 2002 Chiantis.

03:11.492 --> 03:15.761
Ew! No, you're the
fan of 2002 Chiantis.

03:15.763 --> 03:18.430
Wait. What is this?

03:18.731 --> 03:20.632
Looks like one
of Robin's earrings.

03:20.634 --> 03:21.600
Huh! That's weird.

03:21.602 --> 03:24.670
You're the fan...
How did it get in your bed?

03:24.672 --> 03:25.704
I don't know.

03:25.706 --> 03:27.706
Have you been
sleeping with
Robin?

03:27.708 --> 03:28.674
What?
No, of course not!

03:28.676 --> 03:31.877
It probably
got mixed in with
the laundry or something.

03:31.879 --> 03:32.911
Why should I believe you?

03:32.913 --> 03:35.714
Um, maybe because
I've always been
faithful to you,

03:35.716 --> 03:39.518
while
you've cheated on me,
like, six times, bitch.

03:39.520 --> 03:40.352
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

03:40.354 --> 03:41.486
Snap!
Cold-blooded!

03:41.488 --> 03:42.888
Right? Right?

03:42.890 --> 03:45.657
Yeah, I totally
should have said that.

03:45.659 --> 03:46.592
Why should I believe you?

03:46.594 --> 03:53.632
Um, maybe
because I've always been
faithful to you, while you...

03:53.634 --> 03:55.834
I love you.

03:55.836 --> 03:57.903
I knew this was a mistake.

03:57.905 --> 04:00.739
That's it. It's over.

04:01.641 --> 04:04.409
And that was it. She left.

04:04.411 --> 04:05.978
(SIGHS) What a story.

04:05.980 --> 04:08.447
So brave of you to
share that.

04:08.449 --> 04:10.916
Wait.
Those are
your pajamas?

04:10.918 --> 04:12.851
You sleep in
a pajama suit?

04:12.853 --> 04:15.754
Of course.
What do you
think I sleep in?

04:15.756 --> 04:16.788
A coffin.

04:16.790 --> 04:19.958
Dude, that doesn't
look comfortable
at all.

04:19.960 --> 04:21.526
You're wearing a tie.

04:21.528 --> 04:24.429
First of all,
it's a sleeping cravat.

04:24.431 --> 04:26.632
Second,
it's not about comfort.

04:26.634 --> 04:28.767
It's about looking good
all the time.

04:28.769 --> 04:30.869
Why do you have to
look good all the time?

04:30.871 --> 04:33.438
Marshall, let
me tell you a little
story about something

04:33.440 --> 04:35.974
that happened
a couple of months back.

04:35.976 --> 04:37.643
(DOORBELL RINGING)

04:43.650 --> 04:46.518
Hi.
We were just having a
"Who's hornier?" contest

04:46.520 --> 04:49.655
and we spilled massage
oil all over ourselves.

04:49.657 --> 04:52.791
Nice pajamas.
Can we use your shower?

04:54.994 --> 04:57.596
That's not a memory.
That's from a porn movie.

04:57.598 --> 05:02.401
Not just any movie.
That's the exact
scene from...

05:02.403 --> 05:03.535
Never mind.

05:03.537 --> 05:05.904
The point is
it could happen.

05:05.906 --> 05:07.606
And if it did,
and I didn't look

05:07.608 --> 05:09.808
my absolute best
for those greasy
sluts,

05:09.810 --> 05:11.677
I'd regret it forever.

05:11.679 --> 05:12.678
(MARSHALL SNICKERS)

05:12.680 --> 05:15.914
I'm sorry, dude,
but that is just the most
ridiculous sleeping attire

05:15.916 --> 05:18.917
I've ever seen in
my life. Anyway...

05:18.919 --> 05:21.153
Marshall's
wearing a nightgown!

05:21.155 --> 05:22.154
Marshall's
wearing a nightgown!

05:22.156 --> 05:23.855
Hey, guys, you know how in
the future we're always
saying,

05:23.857 --> 05:25.824
"Remember
when Marshall
wore a nightgown?"

05:25.826 --> 05:27.559
This is that time!

05:27.561 --> 05:28.226
It's a nightshirt.

05:28.228 --> 05:31.196
You can
call it a Ninja Star
Danger Jock if you want,

05:31.198 --> 05:33.398
doesn't make you any
less of a cross-dresser.

05:33.400 --> 05:34.766
Whatever, dude. It's comfy.

05:34.768 --> 05:35.701
BARNEY: Uh-huh?
Mmm-hmm.

05:35.703 --> 05:38.737
So, flying to Neverland
with Peter and Tink,
was that amazing?

05:38.739 --> 05:39.738
Ooh! Let me go next!

05:39.740 --> 05:41.840
Was it nice
to finally get out
of that crowded bed

05:41.842 --> 05:43.942
and take Charlie to
the chocolate factory?

05:43.944 --> 05:49.147
Ooh! Me, me, me, me!
Something about Scrooge!

05:49.149 --> 05:51.850
Come on, guys.
I'm carrying the team.

05:51.852 --> 05:52.584
I don't know.

05:52.586 --> 05:54.119
I lived with Marshall
for 12 years.

05:54.121 --> 05:58.223
Any time he's wearing
clothes at all, it's
a victory.

05:59.992 --> 06:01.960
LILY:
Ted, show's
about to start!

06:01.962 --> 06:03.795
Be right there!

06:13.840 --> 06:15.841
<i>(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

06:15.843 --> 06:16.842
(MARSHALL GASPS)

06:16.844 --> 06:19.444
<i>Good morning, New York.</i>
<i>I'm...</i>

06:19.446 --> 06:20.912
Hey!
Whoa!

06:20.914 --> 06:23.915
Marshall,
I just found Robin's
earring on your dresser.

06:23.917 --> 06:26.518
Did you have something to
do with the other one
being in my bed?

06:26.520 --> 06:28.553
What are you talking about?
You've always hated Karen.

06:28.555 --> 06:30.288
You've
been telling me
to break up with her.

06:30.290 --> 06:34.626
You did it. You put
the earring in my bed so
that Karen would find it.

06:34.628 --> 06:35.827
No, Ted! No!
I would never...

06:35.829 --> 06:37.295
Admit it!
There's nothing to admit!

06:37.297 --> 06:39.731
Then why was Robin's
earring on your dresser?

06:39.733 --> 06:40.832
He was accessorizing!

06:40.834 --> 06:44.136
Marshall, I swear to God,
if you don't tell me the
truth right now...

06:44.138 --> 06:47.739
Wait!
Marshall didn't do it.

06:48.841 --> 06:50.208
I did.

06:50.210 --> 06:53.178
I broke you and Karen up.

06:58.184 --> 07:00.118
You broke me
and Karen up?

07:00.120 --> 07:01.553
Are you insane?

07:01.555 --> 07:02.821
What gives you
the right to do that?

07:02.823 --> 07:04.856
Ted,
I did it for
your own good.

07:04.858 --> 07:08.293
You just
weren't seeing
how awful she was.

07:08.295 --> 07:11.096
She failed
the front porch test.

07:11.098 --> 07:12.197
What's the front porch test?

07:12.199 --> 07:16.668
Ted, you, me
and Marshall have been
best friends since college.

07:16.670 --> 07:19.504
Think about how much
we all mean to each other.

07:19.506 --> 07:23.608
So when
I picture the future,
I picture us all together.

07:23.610 --> 07:25.110
<i>How we'll all be retired,</i>

07:25.112 --> 07:27.913
<i>sipping tea</i>
<i>on the front porch</i>
<i>of our beach house,</i>

07:27.915 --> 07:29.648
<i>playing bridge all day.</i>

07:29.650 --> 07:32.117
Okay, bridges are wild.

07:32.119 --> 07:34.619
Four of a bridge
beats a royal bridge.

07:34.621 --> 07:38.757
I see your bridge,
and I raise you
three bridges.

07:38.759 --> 07:40.759
Bridge! I win!

07:40.761 --> 07:43.528
You have no idea how
to play bridge, do you?

07:43.530 --> 07:44.663
We're gonna take a class.

07:44.665 --> 07:46.731
It's important to stay
active.

07:46.733 --> 07:49.801
So whenever
you've been dating
somebody for a while,

07:49.803 --> 07:51.336
I do the
front porch test.

07:51.338 --> 07:56.174
You know, how is this
person gonna fit in with
our group over the years?

07:56.176 --> 07:58.743
And when I think
about Karen there...

07:58.745 --> 08:00.645
Bridge! I win!

08:00.647 --> 08:03.248
Fantastic.
Another game of bridge.

08:03.250 --> 08:05.717
Don't read
a book or anything.

08:05.719 --> 08:08.653
Look, dear, dolphins.

08:08.655 --> 08:09.621
KAREN: They seem happy.

08:09.623 --> 08:12.657
I guess the
chemical runoff from this
elitist beachfront property

08:12.659 --> 08:15.160
hasn't rotted out
their blowholes yet.

08:15.162 --> 08:17.863
It will.
That water
will kill you.

08:17.865 --> 08:20.665
It is a toxic death trap.

08:20.667 --> 08:22.501
I'm gonna take a dip.

08:22.503 --> 08:23.702
I'll join you.

08:23.704 --> 08:26.304
Karen failed
the front porch test.

08:26.306 --> 08:27.472
She had to go.

08:27.474 --> 08:29.207
I can't believe you did that.

08:29.209 --> 08:33.178
Ted,
think about how awesome
you, me and Marshall are.

08:33.180 --> 08:36.214
Seriously, think about it.

08:38.684 --> 08:41.086
We're pretty awesome.
We're totally awesome!

08:41.088 --> 08:45.757
So whoever you marry,
whoever joins Team Awesome,

08:45.759 --> 08:48.360
the bar is set
pretty damn high.

08:48.362 --> 08:51.696
Look, I'm not saying
what I did was right,
but...

08:51.698 --> 08:52.664
You're better
off without her.

08:52.666 --> 08:55.267
And if Clarence
the angel says it's
true, it must be true.

08:55.269 --> 08:58.236
Okay, you know what?
Fine, make your little jokes.

08:58.238 --> 09:00.171
Seriously,
why would you wear
something like that?

09:00.173 --> 09:01.373
Lots of reasons.

09:01.375 --> 09:02.841
I bet you can't name five.

09:02.843 --> 09:04.309
One,
no need to wear
anything underneath.

09:04.311 --> 09:07.746
I can vouch for that.
Will you cross your
legs, buddy?

09:07.748 --> 09:09.180
Two, sexy.

09:09.182 --> 09:10.148
I can vouch for that.

09:10.150 --> 09:12.284
Will you uncross
your legs, buddy?

09:12.286 --> 09:16.087
Three, my
grandpa Olaf wore one,
and he lived to be 107.

09:16.089 --> 09:20.292
Four, no elastic waistband
leaving its judgmental
pink teeth marks

09:20.294 --> 09:21.426
around my Thanksgiving belly.

09:21.428 --> 09:26.531
And five, every night
when I go to sleep,
it's the freest,

09:26.533 --> 09:32.871
<i>most wonderful</i>
<i>feeling in the world.</i>
<i>I feel like I'm flying.</i>

09:32.873 --> 09:35.307
<i>(CHEERFUL MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

09:37.577 --> 09:40.211
<i>So that's how I go</i>
<i>to bed every night,</i>

09:40.213 --> 09:43.715
happy, weightless,
with a heart full
of joy.

09:43.717 --> 09:45.450
What about you?

09:45.452 --> 09:50.789
I have to
lie perfectly still so I
don't wrinkle my suit-jamas.

09:50.791 --> 09:54.225
But at least I'm
not wearing a dress.

09:55.027 --> 09:57.963
(SIGHS) So, how mad are you?

09:57.965 --> 09:59.331
I don't know. I mean,

09:59.333 --> 10:02.968
I guess if you guys
feel that strongly
about Karen,

10:02.970 --> 10:04.869
then maybe it
was for the best.

10:04.871 --> 10:05.937
I really am sorry.

10:05.939 --> 10:10.008
I hated
doing that again,
but Karen had to go.

10:10.010 --> 10:15.580
Again? Wait. How many times
have you broken me up with
a girlfriend?

10:15.582 --> 10:17.082
Never! Six.

10:17.084 --> 10:19.985
Like who?
No one! Angie.

10:20.820 --> 10:21.953
Sophomore year.

10:21.955 --> 10:28.059
She was just using
you to get back at her ex,
and you clearly didn't see it,

10:28.061 --> 10:31.730
<i>so one day when</i>
<i>she was taking</i>
<i>a nap...</i>

10:46.045 --> 10:48.580
Creed?

10:48.582 --> 10:52.417
Oh, my God, I have
to break up with her.

10:52.419 --> 10:55.654
So that's where
my Creed CD went.

10:55.656 --> 10:56.588
Who else?

10:56.590 --> 10:58.390
Remember that
weird sci-fi girl

10:58.392 --> 11:01.026
who wanted you
to propose after,
like, two months?

11:01.028 --> 11:05.830
You barely even liked her, but
you were still thinking about
it, so...

11:05.832 --> 11:07.866
<i>(SCI-FI MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

11:07.868 --> 11:12.337
<i>Listen, Ted, you're great,</i>
<i>and this is so difficult,</i>

11:12.339 --> 11:15.707
<i>but I think</i>
<i>we're looking</i>
<i>for different things.</i>

11:15.709 --> 11:20.578
<i>So, live long and prosper.</i>
<i>Whatever.</i>

11:23.082 --> 11:25.083
(ROARING)

11:25.085 --> 11:27.619
That was you?
This is insane!

11:27.621 --> 11:32.490
Ted, I did those
things to help you.
You're a commitment junkie.

11:32.492 --> 11:34.125
You fall in love
with these women

11:34.127 --> 11:35.026
even if they
don't deserve you.

11:35.028 --> 11:38.063
What if one of those
women was supposed to be
the mother of my children?

11:38.065 --> 11:40.932
If there was ever the
tiniest chance of that,

11:40.934 --> 11:42.500
I swear I didn't do anything.

11:42.502 --> 11:45.070
Like with Victoria or Stella.

11:45.072 --> 11:46.905
Or Robin.

11:48.107 --> 11:49.741
Or Robin.

11:49.743 --> 11:51.743
Robin, Robin...

11:51.745 --> 11:54.479
Did you break us up, too?

11:54.481 --> 11:55.980
Did you break us up, too?

11:55.982 --> 11:59.017
Stop talking to me
like I'm your enemy!

11:59.019 --> 12:00.118
You weep for these women,

12:00.120 --> 12:04.089
but you have the luxury
of not knowing what I know,

12:04.091 --> 12:05.623
that those breakups,
while tragic,

12:05.625 --> 12:10.095
probably saved you
from a crappy and very
expensive first marriage.

12:10.097 --> 12:11.830
Did you break
me and Robin up?

12:11.832 --> 12:14.466
You don't
want the truth
because deep down,

12:14.468 --> 12:16.701
you want me out there
watching out for you.

12:16.703 --> 12:19.170
And deep down, you know
that none of those women

12:19.172 --> 12:21.873
were ever gonna be the
mother of your children.

12:21.875 --> 12:23.508
Did you break
me and Robin up?

12:23.510 --> 12:24.509
I did what I had to do.

12:24.511 --> 12:25.944
Did you break
me and Robin up?

12:25.946 --> 12:28.546
You're damn right I did!

12:31.617 --> 12:36.221
Marshall, your grandpa Olaf
was a wise man.

12:36.223 --> 12:38.022
(MARSHALL SIGHS)

12:41.260 --> 12:42.961
You broke me and Robin up?

12:42.963 --> 12:45.130
No, it's not...
I cannot believe this.

12:45.132 --> 12:46.765
I need another drink.

12:46.767 --> 12:48.800
You know, I feel
a little breeze
down there.

12:48.802 --> 12:49.334
It's nice.

12:49.336 --> 12:52.270
You think that's something?
Stand over this heating vent.

12:52.272 --> 12:56.174
It's like
your junk is on
a tropical island.

12:57.042 --> 12:58.877
Little Barney says,
<i>"Mahalo."</i>

12:58.879 --> 12:59.711
Mmm-hmm.

12:59.713 --> 13:02.147
Seriously,
what is wrong
with you, Lily?

13:02.149 --> 13:03.114
How could you do that?

13:03.116 --> 13:05.150
I did this
because I care about you!

13:05.152 --> 13:09.087
I am so glad that is
the one you watched!

13:09.089 --> 13:11.890
Dear God,
what happened to you?

13:13.726 --> 13:14.959
You didn't watch my show?

13:14.961 --> 13:19.097
Oh! The show. Sorry.
Something special
happen?

13:21.000 --> 13:23.134
(SIGHS) Same old same-old.

13:23.136 --> 13:25.937
Lily just told us that
she broke you and me up.

13:25.939 --> 13:29.007
What? Broke us up?
What does that even mean?

13:29.009 --> 13:31.142
And why
are these guys
wearing nightgowns?

13:31.144 --> 13:32.210
Nightshirt.
Nightshirt.

13:32.212 --> 13:33.812
It's a nightshirt.
It's called
a nightshirt, Robin.

13:33.814 --> 13:36.047
Turns out Lily
has taken it upon
herself to sabotage

13:36.049 --> 13:38.116
many of my relationships,
including ours.

13:38.118 --> 13:39.918
No. Robin was different.

13:39.920 --> 13:41.186
I didn't want you two
to break up,

13:41.188 --> 13:44.889
but you wanted completely
different things out of life

13:44.891 --> 13:46.624
and refused
to deal with it.

13:46.626 --> 13:49.894
I could just
picture that
front porch.

13:49.896 --> 13:51.029
Hmm. Two of hearts.

13:51.031 --> 13:53.932
Just like the hearts
of the two children
I never had

13:53.934 --> 13:57.001
because my lovely wife
hates kids.

13:57.770 --> 13:58.436
Mmm, a deuce.

13:58.438 --> 14:05.109
Exactly what my career dropped
once I decided to settle down
and marry Ted.

14:05.111 --> 14:07.979
Bridge! I win.

14:07.981 --> 14:11.049
Well, I do not like
that scenario one bit.

14:11.051 --> 14:15.253
All I tried
to do was get you guys
to talk about your issues.

14:15.255 --> 14:17.455
<i>I didn't know I was</i>
<i>feeding you the words</i>

14:17.457 --> 14:19.157
<i>that would lead</i>
<i>to your breakup.</i>

14:19.159 --> 14:23.161
Hey, here's a fun question,
just for fun.

14:23.163 --> 14:26.030
Where do you see
yourself in five
years?

14:26.032 --> 14:29.367
You know what's fun?
Fun questions.

14:29.369 --> 14:32.337
Where do you see
yourself in five
years?

14:32.339 --> 14:34.205
Where do you see
yourself in five
years?

14:34.207 --> 14:35.940
Where do you see yourself?

14:35.942 --> 14:37.508
Not
to put words
in your mouth,

14:37.510 --> 14:40.178
but you probably
want to be married.

14:40.180 --> 14:42.046
I probably
want to be married.

14:42.048 --> 14:45.216
You probably want to
be in Tokyo or Paris.

14:45.218 --> 14:49.287
I probably want
to be in Argentina.

14:49.289 --> 14:50.388
Argentina?

14:50.390 --> 14:52.857
Or Tokyo or Paris.

14:52.859 --> 14:55.827
We have
an expiration
date, don't we?

14:55.829 --> 14:57.228
Oh, my God.
Lily,

14:57.230 --> 14:59.898
you can't manipulate
people like that!

14:59.900 --> 15:02.066
I've known you 12 years,
and I can honestly say,

15:02.068 --> 15:03.968
I have never been
more furious at you!

15:03.970 --> 15:05.236
Look, I didn't mean to...
I was just...

15:05.238 --> 15:07.138
No!
I don't even
want to hear it!

15:07.140 --> 15:07.939
Whoa, whoa, whoa!

15:07.941 --> 15:10.208
Settle down!
Let's just settle down!

15:10.210 --> 15:12.176
Now, I have one question.

15:12.178 --> 15:14.178
What do these bad
boys feel like in bed?

15:14.180 --> 15:15.914
Come on. Let's go see.

15:15.916 --> 15:19.918
So, if it weren't for you,
Ted and I might still be
dating?

15:19.920 --> 15:22.854
Or you
would have stayed
together far too long,

15:22.856 --> 15:25.390
had
an incredibly
bitter breakup

15:25.392 --> 15:27.091
and not even
remained friends,

15:27.093 --> 15:30.061
and then
you and I would never
have become best friends.

15:30.063 --> 15:33.031
Don't even say that.
Okay?

15:33.599 --> 15:34.232
Stop hugging!

15:34.234 --> 15:39.170
Lily, you had no right
to interfere in my
relationships.

15:39.172 --> 15:40.204
You got lucky. Okay?

15:40.206 --> 15:43.174
You met the love of your life
in a dorm hallway when you
were 18.

15:43.176 --> 15:45.310
But that doesn't give
you the right to play
God

15:45.312 --> 15:47.045
to the rest of us
mortals down here

15:47.047 --> 15:48.346
who are still
looking for someone.

15:48.348 --> 15:51.049
You're so concerned about
who you and Marshall are
gonna end up

15:51.051 --> 15:52.283
on that front porch with.

15:52.285 --> 15:56.988
Well, you know what?
You can have it to
yourselves.

15:57.957 --> 15:59.223
(DOOR SLAMS)

16:01.026 --> 16:03.094
What happened
to your jacket?

16:03.096 --> 16:06.030
Soot, bread crumbs, placenta.

16:06.032 --> 16:08.599
Did you at least TiVo it?

16:08.601 --> 16:09.968
(SIGHS)

16:10.302 --> 16:12.370
So, you're this
comfy every night,

16:12.372 --> 16:14.205
and Lily still
has sex with you?

16:14.207 --> 16:17.542
Yeah. That's what
marriage is all about,
man, unconditional love.

16:17.544 --> 16:21.312
You can wear
whatever you want
and still get laid.

16:21.314 --> 16:24.082
Tell me more
about being married.

16:24.084 --> 16:26.150
Well, sometimes,
when you're married,

16:26.152 --> 16:30.054
you wake up to the smell of
breakfast already on the
table.

16:30.056 --> 16:32.090
And coffee, too?
And coffee, too.

16:32.092 --> 16:37.261
Sometimes,
she'll even put out a
vase of freshly cut flowers.

16:37.263 --> 16:39.063
I love flowers.

16:39.065 --> 16:39.664
(MARSHALL CHUCKLES)

16:39.666 --> 16:43.334
And sometimes, when you're
worried you've made all
the wrong decisions in life,

16:43.336 --> 16:47.305
and you're not nearly
the man you want to be,
what does she do then?

16:47.307 --> 16:52.210
Well, she tells
you that you're great
and it's all gonna be okay.

16:52.212 --> 16:55.013
(CHUCKLES) That's wonderful.

16:55.015 --> 17:00.151
And she'll help you find
other girls to have sex
with?

17:02.588 --> 17:03.221
I mean, I guess.

17:03.223 --> 17:07.925
Maybe
if you agreed upon
that beforehand, yeah.

17:07.927 --> 17:08.526
Mmm.

17:08.528 --> 17:12.997
Little guy had a big day.
We'll talk about it tomorrow.

17:12.999 --> 17:14.999
Sweet dreams, slugger.

17:16.068 --> 17:19.971
<i>(CHEERFUL MUSIC PLAYING)</i>

17:28.714 --> 17:32.617
<i>OLDER TED: The next night,</i>
<i>I was still angry at your</i>
<i>aunt Lily.</i>

17:32.619 --> 17:34.185
<i>Until...</i>

17:34.187 --> 17:37.555
Hi.
Hi. What are you...

17:39.992 --> 17:42.627
Lily came by and
explained everything.

17:42.629 --> 17:46.564
And she gave me
this note for you.

17:46.566 --> 17:47.899
(TED SIGHS)

17:49.601 --> 17:51.135
<i>LILY: "Ted, I'm sorry.</i>

17:51.137 --> 17:52.837
<i>"It doesn't matter</i>
<i>to me who you marry.</i>

17:52.839 --> 17:57.708
<i>"I know they'll be awesome</i>
<i>because they'll think you are.</i>

17:57.710 --> 17:58.609
<i>"To show I mean it,</i>

17:58.611 --> 18:02.313
<i>"I put together</i>
<i>a little surprise for</i>
<i>you and Karen upstairs.</i>

18:02.315 --> 18:03.314
<i>"Love, Lily."</i>

18:03.316 --> 18:05.917
<i>MARSHALL: "P.S.</i>
<i>Sorry the envelope</i>
<i>was already open.</i>

18:05.919 --> 18:09.687
<i>"I had to read what</i>
<i>she wrote. Marshall."</i>

18:09.689 --> 18:12.390
Sabotaging our relationship?
I got to say,

18:12.392 --> 18:15.493
even using
the specially-ordered,
extra-low bar by which I

18:15.495 --> 18:19.397
judge your friends,
Lily really outdid
herself this time.

18:19.399 --> 18:21.699
Obviously,
we can't ever
see her again.

18:21.701 --> 18:25.536
I know.
It's a big loss, right?

18:28.273 --> 18:30.942
Hey,
remember your
old college roommate?

18:30.944 --> 18:35.413
He was married to that
shrill, little idiot girl.

18:35.415 --> 18:39.884
Marshall.
Oh, it's been so long.

18:39.886 --> 18:41.786
God, I hated him.

18:41.788 --> 18:44.455
Anyway, here's his obituary.

18:44.990 --> 18:47.692
And I realized,
maybe it shouldn't
matter what my friends

18:47.694 --> 18:50.895
think of my girlfriend,
but it sure as hell
matters what

18:50.897 --> 18:53.965
my girlfriend
thinks of my friends.

18:53.967 --> 18:56.801
Wow. So you ended it?

18:56.803 --> 18:58.903
Yeah.

18:58.905 --> 19:03.241
So if you want
to be my plus one,
Lily's a damn good cook.

19:03.243 --> 19:03.674
ROBIN: Mmm!

19:03.676 --> 19:08.179
Beef pot pie, mac and cheese,
homemade buttermilk biscuits.

19:08.181 --> 19:11.749
Wow, no wonder
Marshall dies at 68.

19:11.751 --> 19:13.417
(ROBIN LAUGHS)

19:13.419 --> 19:14.118
Thank you.

19:14.120 --> 19:17.054
<i>OLDER TED:</i>
<i>So, Robin and I</i>
<i>enjoyed a gourmet dinner.</i>

19:17.056 --> 19:18.256
<i>Well, for her</i>
<i>it was breakfast.</i>

19:18.258 --> 19:22.593
<i>And we ended up</i>
<i>doing exactly what Lily</i>
<i>wanted us to do all along,</i>

19:22.595 --> 19:25.363
<i>we talked about</i>
<i>our relationship.</i>

19:25.964 --> 19:29.300
So,
Lily broke
us up, sort of.

19:29.302 --> 19:30.902
Yeah.

19:31.136 --> 19:33.070
Kind of makes you wonder.

19:33.072 --> 19:34.138
Yeah.

19:34.140 --> 19:36.174
I mean,
if it weren't for her,

19:36.176 --> 19:39.410
would we still be
dating right now?

19:39.412 --> 19:40.978
Maybe.

19:41.713 --> 19:44.982
But
Lily was right.
We weren't ready.

19:44.984 --> 19:48.786
We both needed to move on,
do our own thing.

19:48.788 --> 19:50.188
Still do, I guess.

19:50.190 --> 19:51.889
Mmm-hmm.

19:53.091 --> 19:54.892
We should make a pact.

19:54.894 --> 19:58.129
If the years go by,
and we both turn 40,

19:58.131 --> 20:00.731
and we're still single, we...

20:05.837 --> 20:11.042
Robin Scherbatsky,
will you be my backup wife?

20:11.610 --> 20:14.078
A girl always dreams
of hearing those words.

20:14.080 --> 20:17.481
Yes! Yes!
A million times, yes!

20:17.483 --> 20:19.383
(ROBIN GIGGLING)

20:22.788 --> 20:24.388
(SOFTLY) Thank you.

20:24.856 --> 20:26.991
All right, it's a deal.
Yeah.

20:26.993 --> 20:27.858
(BOTH EXCLAIM)

20:27.860 --> 20:30.728
(CLEARING THROAT)
So, should we set up
some ground rules for this?

20:30.730 --> 20:31.128
Okay, like what?

20:31.130 --> 20:33.798
I don't know. Like neither
one of us can get super fat.
Stuff like that.

20:33.800 --> 20:36.167
Okay, I only have one,
you can't wear a nightshirt.

20:36.169 --> 20:38.135
I will never
wear a nightshirt.

20:38.137 --> 20:39.971
Thank God.

20:43.942 --> 20:45.810
(DOORBELL RINGING)

20:47.646 --> 20:48.980
(GRUNTS)

20:56.788 --> 20:59.357
Never mind.

20:59.825 --> 21:01.058
No!
